Concurrency control when there are multiple threads. 
Concurrency control if our application is made distributed and we are using a central database. 
Concurrency when both app and db are distributed.



1. 

Single machine (multi-threaded app)

Problem

Multiple threads accessing shared memory/resources → race conditions.

What can go wrong
Lost updates
Dirty reads (in-memory)
Inconsistent state


Solutions:

Locks (mutex / synchronized)
Only one thread enters critical section

Read-Write locks
Many readers, one writer

Thread-safe structures
ConcurrentHashMap, blocking queues


_______________



2. 

Distributed app + single central DB


Problem

Multiple app instances → all hitting same DB concurrently.
Now DB becomes the “source of truth + concurrency controller”.

What can go wrong

Double booking / double spend
Lost updates across services



Solutions (most important interview area):

1. DB locks

Row-level locks (SELECT ... FOR UPDATE
Pessimistic locking
Good for strict consistency


2. Optimistic locking (very common)
Add version column


Update like:

UPDATE table
SET value = ?, version = version + 1
WHERE id = ? AND version = ?
If 0 rows updated → conflict detected



3. Unique constraints (
Prevent duplicates at DB level
Example: booking_id unique


4. Idempotency keys
API safe retry mechanism
Prevent duplicate processing due to retries


5. Transactions
ACID guarantees inside DB
Ensures atomicity across multiple updates


_________________

3.


Fully distributed system (app + DB both distributed)

Now it gets interesting. No single global lock exists.

Problem:

Multiple services
Multiple DBs
Network failures
Partial updates



A. Distributed locking (careful with this)
Redis lock / Zookeeper ..


Probelms :

Network partition issues
Deadlocks if not handled properly
Expiry-based locks can be unsafe





B. Saga pattern (VERY important)

Instead of one big transaction:

You do steps + compensating actions.

Example:

Payment service charges money
Order service creates order
Inventory service reserves stock

If step 3 fails:

Compensate step 2 (cancel order)
Compensate step 1 (refund)

Types:

Choreography (event-driven)
Orchestration (central coordinator)


SEE In Hotel Booking System HLD Section



C. Eventual consistency
Systems sync asynchronously
Data may be temporarily inconsistent



D. Idempotency everywhere

Because:

retries WILL happen
network WILL fail

So every operation must be safe to retry




E. Message queues

Kafka / SQS style flow:

Producer sends event
Consumer processes async

But then you need:

exactly-once or at-least-once handling
deduplication



F. Outbox pattern (important interview concept)
Write DB + event in same transaction
Then async publisher sends event to queue

Prevents:

“DB updated but event not sent” issue





| Level              | Problem             | Tool                                       |
| ------------------ | ------------------- | ------------------------------------------ |
| Threads in process | shared memory       | locks, atomics                             |
| Multi-service + DB | concurrent requests | DB locks, optimistic locking, transactions |
| Fully distributed  | partial failures    | saga, events, idempotency                  |



